title: RV WASHER, SPIN DRYER
text:
Wow. How great is this. No more waiting around in a dirty laundry room while traveling. This little gem fits in my shower. I use a bucket to catch the rince and spin water for the next wash.

This is an update after several years of using this while camping with my RV. So many people are complaining of fitting the hose into sink faucets. If you watch the video the lady simply pushes the hose up onto the faucet but we RVers know about the "water bandIt". That works great to get water from any faucet. Put the hose into the bandit and push that onto your faucet. Mine is still working and spinning my clothes almost DRY, a few minutes on a wooden rack and they are good to go. One more hint adding an ounce of vinegar softens the clothes. I also use the miracle clothes balls instead of detergent so I can dump the water out on the ground. Amazing how much dirt these balls get out of the clothes. These balls are regenerated by placing in the sun for a few hours. I wash once a week when boondocking because I'm a nurse and refuse to use public laundry rooms. The other gadget I use is the clothes dryer that shoots hot air up around the clothes. I put it under the wooden rack or clothes hung on the shower rod when I am plugged in to electricity at an RV park. I don't need the plastic bag that comes with it to enclose the bag.

title: The MORE filter works great, but note its made in China
text:
I have been trying different lower-cost filters for a while. They are all made in China, even the so-called OEM Maytag branded model that sells for nearly twice the price. The quality control standards in China are poor. The MORE filter works great, installs same as the OEM, and the water tastes the same to me as when I used the Maytag filter. If I could find a reasonably priced filter made in the USA I'd get that one. But for the price, the MORE filter is fine. 4 stars because its made in China.

Update July 2020. I'm still using the MORE filter and I'm still happy with it. I have used it now for several 6 month cycles and I have not had any problems. The filtered water tastes fine. The only reason I would change to a different filter is if I could find one made in the USA at a reasonable price. I'm still taking off one star for "made in China".

title: New Viking 30" gas range a winner
text: I had purchased a Wolf 30" gas range but the infrared broiler was not as good as my 16 year old Viking gas range.  Wolf is a very reputable and reliable company and took back  the range that I had for a few months and returned my money (a first class outfit).  So I purchased a new Viking range and am thrilled with some of the new features.  The self cleaning ones have been discontinued so this one is not self cleaning.  The shelves in the oven roll out and one burner has more BTUs  than the rest for big jobs.  Also the infrared oven is excellent and the top is now sealed so liquid does not drip down into the guts of the oven and rust it out like the old one.  The company is not as generous as Wolf and made me purchase a new set of knobs with the color of my choice (black) for better visibility and would not take back the silver ones as an exchange.  The only annoying feature of all the new ranges is that they turn off when the oven gets very hot, even when you are using the IR broiler.  I crack the door open to cool it to defeat this stupid feature.  The IR broiler can be used with the convection fan and this is excellent on the Viking but not allowed on the Wolf.

title: I have one from 1996
text: I am writing this review one from 1996.  Everything still works although I replaced many parts related to all the ignitors including the one for the infrared oven.  Also some little gadgets in the control knobs to prevent ignitors from firing in error.  Karl Schaedel Co in PA helps you diagnose the problems and sells the repair part.  If I had to pay for repairs I would have thrown the whole thing out years ago.  I like the high BTU top burners and particularly the infrared oven that acts like the barbecue grill.  The infrared broiler has lasted nearly 20 years now and makes it possible to grill meat and fish during  the winter without going outside, although sometimes the flames inside the over get too exciting.  The weakness from the beginning has been the while enamel shell that I have sanded and repainted repeatedly and has I now gotten to the point of having to look for a new 30 inch wide gas range.  The Wolf infrared broiler's configuration seems to have mainly "dead spots" so I will  have to go with Viking again for the infrared broiler.  Apparently the new broilers can cycle on and off because of more conservative thermostat control but if you leave the door a little open, it will keep it cool enough to keep the broiler on. title: Fully restored my LG Steam dryer
text: [[VIDEOID:183e6f4b86bf51e723b3b8b53b9c63ba]] My wife and I love our LG Steam Dryer and Washer units.  Last week the dryer started making a really bad screeching sound and I knew immediately that the drum rollers were going out.  I ordered the Dryer Repair Kit and it came the very next day.  The hardest part of the repair was getting to the back of my dryer since our laundry room is more of an overgrown closet than an actual room.  At any rate I managed to get the 3 screws off the back of the dryer by reaching OVER the dryer while standing on a step stool.  Once the 3 screws come off, the top of the dryer slides off towards the rear.  The rest of the dryer comes apart in a fairly straightforward manner.  I took a lot of Pix with my Iphone just to make sure it went back together correctly.  Once the control panel came off and the door assembly was removed, it was easy to remove the rest of the front panel supports and the drum itself.  I was then able to rotate the remaining base of the dryer since it was much lighter, to get to the rear screws that hold on the mounting plate that holds the 2 rear drum wheels.  Removed all the wheels and replaced them with the wheels in the kit.  Next replaced the idler pulley, and the drum with the new belt.  Re-attached the control panel, front door etc.  Started the dryer and it now runs perfectly!  Saved a ton of money in the process.

text: If you were like me, you searched for a replacement valve for your furnace humidifier and became confused by the large selection and wide range of prices.  Don't be confused by a specific brand or the different applications that they list.  As long as fittings look like the ones one your valve, this one will work for you.  Every furnace valve works on standard furnace power which is universal in North America.  This is a simple repair that anyone with basic wiring skills can do.  the voltage involved cannot harm you.  Just turn off the water valve,  undo your fitting, cut your wires and remove the old valve.  Splice the new wires onto the old ones (no positive or negative since it's AC), screw the new valve back into position, screw the water lines back on (follow the arrows for flow direction) and turn your water back on. title: Don't fill it up!
text:
I am so grateful for the reviews! The tips and insights were helpful, so now this is a great product for me.
My washer conked out and the new one was about a month in coming. This item in the meantime is great. Here's a summary of the best tips:
This is a small appliance, someone described it like a blender. It is Not a washer replacement, so change that perception or you'll be disappointed.
Fill it to the lowest line load. The second line makes no sense. Water will spill out, even on the gentle cycle.
Don't fill it up. Clothes need to be able to move with water around them. I might do an adult wool blend sweater and a couple pairs of socks, but not jeans and a sweater: too much material for the appliance to handle well.
Make sure the bucket sits properly on the motor and is against a wall or something. This will prevent the bucket spinning. The weight of clothes and water should provide support as well.
Use a tiny amount of detergent. I'm amazed at how clean and nice smelling the clothes are after washing in this thing. What have I been doing up to this point?
Run a rinse cycle when desired. Works great with liquid fabric softener.
Dump out water, squeeze clothes, hang up or throw 'em in a dryer.
I wipe the washer down underneath-to prevent rust I saw in some pictures-and unplug it if I'm not using it for a while.
So full marks and a high recommendation. It isn't as pretty as some of the other washers, but it does the job and that's why I bought it.

title: The right handle- but it's difficult to replace.
text: The door handle arrived within a few days. It was the correct part for our microwave. It was somewhat difficult to pull the inside lining off of the microwave- I found a video on YouTube that offered suggestions on how to access the screws that hold the handle. With the door open, unscrew the three screws on the inside of the door. Then, slide a flathead screwdriver (I actually used a butter knife, but a flat putty knife might work even better) under the veneer at the top left corner of the inside of the door and gently "pry" the liner out. It's difficult at the beginning, as there are plastic fasteners every few inches (hidden from view) that hold the door together. (As opposed to the small metal clips that are visible). When the first fastener "popped", I feared I had damaged the door, but it was fine- I was then able to slide my butter knife down the door and pry the fasteners out until the inside lining came out. I was afraid to take the entire liner out, but it eventually fell out on its own as the fasteners are the only parts keeping it in place. I would actually suggest taking the liner completely out altogether, because once the handle screws are revealed, you will need a Phillips screwdriver to unscrew the handle screws. If the inside lining is still in place, I think most screwdrivers would be too long to fit in between the liner and the screw. Once the screws are out, I saved them and put the new handle on. It seems like it would be easy to torque too hard and crack the handle, so be careful! I was not able to get this part to be flush against the door- (there is probably a 1mm gap between the handle and the door, thus the 4 star rating- also, some instructions to replace would have been nice). Once the new handle is on, the lining snaps right back in easily. Screw in the three door screws and you're ready for more TV dinners... I was careful, but our microwave still sustained some minor damage and part of the door cracked because I screwed one of the door screws back in too hard... The whole process takes about 20-30 minutes...

title: Sturdy Temperature/Humidity Tool
text:
When I was having problems with my air conditioning unit, the technician that came to my home and has since maintenanced my unit suggested that I monitor the machine's output by using a Fluke Meter. In his opinion as a professional, Fluke makes a product that is reliable and sturdy.

I use my [[ASIN:B0089N2ZH6 Fluke 62 MAX Plus Infrared Thermometer, AA Battery, -20 to +1202 Degree F Range]] to monitor the temperature of certain craft products that require mixing at certain temperatures. I have used this product for years without needing replacement.

This Fluke 971 Temperature Humidity Meter is built with the same sturdy quality. The case is strong and will not break when accidentally dropped. Its easy to use--a press of a button puts the meter into action. The back lighting is a good feature.

Other reviewers have mentioned that the meter fluctuates and also requires calibration at over-the-top costs. I cannot testify to this as I am only using the meter to check the temperature and humidity in the rooms in my home. Yes, at initial turn-on, the read fluctuates, but after waiting a few seconds, it settles down into one reading. I have no alternative in which to test the accuracy of the humidity but, I am not a professional contractor and have no need of such accuracy.

Bottom line? Fluke makes a good sturdy product. For home use, this Temperature/Humidity Meter is adequate, however, I would heed some of the other reviewers who speak from a professional vantage point. I do like product and would buy another Fluke product when the need arises.

title: An almost perfect electric range, but with aggravations
text:
I am a serious home French pastry chef. Five years ago I bought the then-current version of this stove. My main interest was the convection oven. Indeed, this oven is extremely good in even baking. There were many other features I liked, although I found the controls a bit confusing. For guests and first timers, the controls can be VERY confusing. I would still have given it 5 stars.

I bought this new version for a different home. There is one change that I find so annoying that I downgraded this new model in my view to 4 stars. This is the temperature readout for the main oven.

On most digital readouts, including the earlier version of this stove, you start by setting the target temperature. Then as the oven heats up, it shows the actual temp. This gives you an idea of how much longer you need to wait. If you are cooking something at a non-critical 350 degrees, you might just put it in at 325. Similarly, if you open the oven, say to turn a tray, you know exactly how much the temp has dropped. Not with this new version.

You set the target temp, then wait for a long beep to tell you the oven has reached the

target temp. There is no way to tell the current temp. While heating up, some lights flash in an incomprehensible sequence. Neither the manual nor Fridigaire customer support could explain what those lights mean. Even with a totally manual oven (like the small side oven here), you can get an idea of current temp by rotating the knob and listening for the thermostat click.

Another downgrade was the minimum temp setting on the old oven was 100 degrees, a sometimes useful setting in baking. The minimum on this oven is 150.

I wrote to Frigidaire, an actual letter to the director of marketing with the comments above. He never replied.
____________________________
A belated followup: It took a while, but eventually I did get some very helpful responses from Frigidaire customer support and their marketing department. I am very happy with the stove.

I tried it with the metal pan that comes with the oven first, but then I bought the grille tray made for this oven (comes separately from the GE website, which had the best online price) and they came out even better because the ridges in the tray lift them up out of the cooking juices/grease. Another reviewer noted that the preheat time is a little longish, and while I agree, the speed cook function for many foods that doesn't require preheating due to the instant halogen heat in the upper Advantium oven.  I bought this model on the recommendation of a neighbor who adores hers, and I must say the advice was spot-on!  I'm very happy with it.  Also...the lighting is terrific! The only advice I would give you is that since the lighting is LED, your food won't look as brown as it would in an older oven with incandescent lighting which is not as bright, so at first you might be tempted to overcook things a bit while looking for that nice golden-brown on your muffins or what have you.  The automatic settings for weight and food type have worked well for me so far, and the defrost mode is almost as good as my old Samsung over-the-range microwave (which was the be all-end all of microwaves for me, but won't fit in my new kitchen).  It comes with a cookbook that has speed-cook adjusted recipes, and I have found that Pinterest has several as well. title: If you pick the right seller, you can get a real OEM.
text:
If your LG washing machine starts making strange sounds like grinding during the drain cycles, DON'T WAIT. Get a new pump today and keep it because the washer is soon (within two weeks in our case) going to poop out and give you the "OE" code. When that happens, you'll have the pump on hand instead of having to wait days for it to arrive.

Be careful of the seller or you run the risk of getting a non OEM part. While the price varies, I paid about $9 more and picked Amazon itself as the seller versus any of the other "fulfilled by Amazon" orders which are a grab bag of vendors. Mine appears to be a true LG OEM part.

The best repair guide can be found on YouTube under the title "Washing Machine Repair - Replacing the Drain Pump (LG Part # 4681EA2001T)." That's the video I followed and it took about an hour total. The hardest part is replacing the rubber drain collar around the door. Once you get that, it's game on.

A few tips:
Save all the screws and put them back into the same hole you removed them from. For instance, when you take the front off, put the loose screw back a just a few turns into its hole. There's about a dozen screws, all different, and all hard to tell apart once they're jumbled up.

Make sure you clean all the parts you've removed. The washer gets a lot of scale, funk, fumunda cheese, etc. in all the internals. It's nasty. That soap tray...hot mess to clean it out especially in the far back.

The attached pictures are the box my part came in.

I didn't decide to change out the pump because it was working. The fan was spinning so why replace something that isn't broke? So after going through the laundry list of items to check for with nothing resolving the issue, I decided to just purchase a new pump. What did I have to lose?

Long story short, it worked! So for those trying to figure out the drain issue on your washing machine and thinking that you've already checked your pump because it was spinning and sounded like it was working, think again. For ~$25, this was well worth the price as it was an easy replacement. At least I cleaned ALL of the hoses in the process of figuring out what the issue was. Now I have a brand new washing machine (well like-new)!
